         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Sir:— ¶  ¶ In reference to some recent remarks in your valuable journal, ¶  allow me to state that three leading French authorities in olive culture and the industries connected therewith, give in the...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">89.09.00a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Editor of the Mildura Cultivator</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from 'Olive oil", <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Mildura cultivator</seg>, 19 September 1889, p. 9 (B89.09.04).</p>
               </note>Sir:—</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In reference to some recent remarks in your valuable journal,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. L. Thompson (1889) is the text of an address delivered before the Mildura Settlers' Association on 19 August. Thompson refuted M's assertion that it was necessary to avoid crushing the kernels to prevent a disagreeable taste’s being imparted to the oil. Thompson cited B80.13.07, p. 201; the same statement was included in the then current edition, B88.12.01, p. 260.</p>
               </note> allow me to state that three leading French authorities in olive culture and the industries connected therewith, give in their well-known works the following statements: Mons. Coutance: By light pressure a first-class olive oil is obtained; by stronger pressure a second quality; with the aid of boiling water a third quality.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Coutance (1877) pp. 281-302, especially p. 290.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mons. Reynaud: To obtain first class oil the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">kernel</seg> should <seg style="font-style: italic; ">not</seg> be broken, as it would impair the taste of the oil.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Reynaud (1862), p. 206.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Mons Riondet expresses a similar opinion.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Riondet (1867?), pp. 113ff. [The copy available on Gallica (<ref target="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k9781379f/f11.image.r=Riondet%20L'olivier"
                          rend="Internet%20link"
                          style="color: #0563c1; ">
                        <seg rend="Internet%20link" style="color: #0563c1; ">https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k9781379f/f11.image.r=Riondet%20L'olivier</seg>
                     </ref>) does not have a publication date set in type, but a ‘Depot légal’ stamp is for 1867.]</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Whatever, therefore, the experiences in Australia may have been, there is a good case for recommending that the pressing process for olives should only extend to the pulp, not the stone (putamen), nor the kernel (seed).</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Respectfully yours.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>FERD. VON MUELLER</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
